If I understood correctly, the purpose of your method is to extract an integer part from an arbitrary subtype of `Number`.

For that, you don&#39;t need to reassign the method parameter `t` (*and in general, it&#39;s not a good practice*). And there&#39;s no need to use constructor of `Integer` class (*which is by the way **deprecated***), since Java 1.5 we have [autoboxing][auto], and you don&#39;t need to worry about conversion between wrapper types and primitives.

Method [`Number.intValue()`][intValue] gives you a primitive `int` value, simply return it from the method.

    public static &lt;T extends Number&gt; int calculate(T t) {
        
        return t.intValue();
    }

*Usage example:*

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int i1 = calculate(1);
        int i2 = calculate(9.95);
        int i3 = calculate(new BigDecimal(&quot;10000000.971519&quot;));
    }


   [intValue]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Number.html#intValue()

   [auto]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/data/autoboxing.html

